import numpy as np
np.random.seed(0) # For reproducibility

# Feature distributions based on univariate statistics
target_materials = ["aluminium", "gold", "polypropylene", "plastic"]
target_thicknesses = np.round(np.random.uniform(low=0, high=125, size=(25,))
pulse_widths = np.round(np.random.lognormal(mean=4.96378, sigma=2.05074, size=(25,)).astype(int)  # Log-normally distributed around the median (30) with log scale of variance
energies = np.round(np.random.lognormal(mean=1.6984, sigma=1.51784, size=(25,)).astype(int)  # Log-normally distributed around the median (2.35) with log scale of variance
spot_sizes = np.round(np.random.normal(loc=3.61, scale=0.795, size=(25,))
intensities = np.round(np.random.lognormal(mean=18.4337, sigma=1.84547e+1, size=(25,)).astype(float)  # Log-normally distributed around the median (6.22E+20) with log scale of variance
powers = np.round(np.random.lognormal(mean=13.8584, sigma=2.7212e+13, size=(25,)).astype(float)  # Log-normally distributed around the median (7.68E+13) with log scale of variance
cutoff_energies = np.round(np.random.lognormal(mean=4.8099, sigma=2.05074, size=(25,)).astype(float)  # Log-normally distributed around the median (4.8) with log scale of variance

# Assign target_materials randomly from the given list
target_materials = np.random.choice(target_materials, 25)

data = np.vstack([target_materials, target_thicknesses, pulse_widths, energies, spot_sizes, intensities, powers, cutoff_energies]).T

print(data)
```
